rComments: Here is the thing. The professor is nice during the lecture. All the explanations are clear, the style is funny. However, the midterm is really designed to get your mark down. He even tells you to memorize things from a video, which is absolutely unrelated to ecology in any extent.
This course was not one of the best. The material would seem interesting to only those who are interested in EEB. I hated the midterm it was all analyzing and graphs. Pay attention in his class.

Professor Stinchcombe was funny and concise. The tests were fair and very easy as long as you read the material, any confusing questions on the test will be given as bonus marks after the tests are marked. The class was interesting and designed in a way that makes it possible to get incredibly high marks. An awesome professor and course.
He literally just reads straight off the slides, no point in going to lectures. His wording for tests are really confusing. Goodluck!

Ok so basically Stinchcombe is a really good professor because everything u need to know is on the slides and he just repeats it lol. His tests are mod. You have to remember that one example he said in lecture 7, slide 11 (ex) and like the specifics. Very heavy memorization. -This is BIO120 btw idk about other courses he may teach.
Pretty funny prof that tries to make lecture relatable and interesting. Test questions were as expected. Some questions relate directly back to readings but he tells you that before the test.

Love him!! I'm going to miss him in the second section of the course. Really funny and likeable, and really makes you care about what we're doing to the planet (this course gets pretty depressing towards the end of his section). I look forward to taking more of his courses.

SO many of his exam questions are worded difficultly. For example, his questions ask "which of the following is most likely to be proven false". He's also a big fan of the questions where he lists 5 statements and then has you choose which ones are true or false or can be proven with a complementary graph.
great!
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Accessible outside class', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: He's a great lecturer, and I found the material to be fascinating (if not depressing). His voice was unusual at first, but you get used to it.
He was okay. Pretty mediocre, especially compared to Rowe. Some of the exam questions made no sense and there were no practice exams, which are useful for predicting a prof's style of questioning.
His tests are 70% unrelated to his lecture.
his voice is so annoying..but overall he's ok

Lectures were alright (explained well & material was interesting). Test questions were also very straightforward: either thinking questions asking you to analyze data/predict based on data OR simple knowledge questions. Very good prof.

I took this course a few years ago. I had had this prof as an instructor on a field course and his enthusiasm for Ecology & Evolution was the impetus that pushed me to this stream of biology. He is very personable, quite approachable (when you get to know him) and is good at explaining concepts. He's clear about expectations, and expects a lot.
Loved him!
Annoying tone of voice, you either love it or you hate it. Very boring material in his section.

Maybe his voice will sound better when he hits puberty.  Painful to listen to on the recordings.  Also, barely suppressed his rage when somebody blocked the projector.  He needs to be put on a shelf until he matures.
Clear (but high) expectations, explains things clearly.
He's pretty good.
"does this sound reasnoable?" his favourite quote
great prof.

Has high expectations of students... requiring us to read articles and remember them for a test! Test had errors, but these were fixed. Prof treats and expects you to learn like a university student not a high schooler.

One of multiple professors in BIO150, he lectured for the last portion of first semester and did not compare with the first. However although he gives a lot of articles, they portray the class material well.
